Pierce, Technical Advisor "little by Utile from beginning to end" "jtoco a poo.' initio ad-inftnen” THE ALBUQUERQUE GENEALOGICAL SOCIETY In Cooperation with the Albuquerque Public Library, Special Collections P.O.Box 25512 Albuquerque, New Mexico 87125-0512 © 2004 All Rights Reserved GSI - 3041 Every Name Index Torrance County 1910 United States Census Territory of New Mexico Introduction This edition covers only Torrance County, Territory of New Mexico, as enumerated in the 13th Census of the United States in the year 1910. This index is intended as an aid to researchers by listing surname, first, and middle names (where given), and the page and line where that name may be found in the microfilm record of the Census. It includes every member of the family, not just Head of Household. The present plans are to complete each of the 26 counties of the Territory of New Mexico and compile that data into a computer database where it will be organized into separate County Indexes. Then, they will be combined into one comprehensive set of volumes indexing the entire Territory of New Mexico in the Census of 1910. We attempted to use the spelling used by the Enumerators, even when we knew they were misspelled. However, we have also included an additional listing of the correct spelling of the Head of Household with a reference to the misspelled listing. Three volunteer Indexers worked separately to decipher each name in this Index using photocopies of the microfilm. The First Reader undertook the challenging task of handwriting, line by line, his or her understanding of what the Enumerator had written in 1910. The Second Reader either agreed with the assessment of the First Reader or offered written alternatives. The Third Reader had the benefit of the previous work and could "vote" with either the First or the Second Reader or, in many cases, suggested a third alternative. i The Editor made the final determination as to the correct spelling of the name, often checking against the microfilm. In cases where different spellings seemed possible due to the individual nature of the handwriting of the Enumerator, the Editor elected to enter more than one variation of the name in this Index to aid researchers. In some instances, the Enumerator mistakenly entered the first, middle, and last name instead of using the correct procedure of last, first, and middle. The Editor has entered the name in this Index both ways. There are many instances where it appears that the Enumerator could not spell a name and simply drew a straight line instead of trying to do so. We have attempted to identify these as best we could. The Editor is certain that often the Enumerator did not go to the door - or possibly no one was home and he never went back - and so he filled in the data by entering the husband’s surname with sometimes only a first initial. Then, for the wife, entered only "Mrs." and a child as "Unknown Son". Perhaps he felt he was familiar enough with the man and his family to get them counted but, unfortunately for researchers, not familiar enough to know all the names of those in the household and not willing or able to return to the house to gain more data. It is also probable that when an Enumerator could not find any person at home or could not find a household member willing to participate in the census, he asked neighbors for any information they may have known about the family, however little, and enter it as data. In many cases Enumerators missed whole households. Households in very remote areas may have been missed or purposefully omitted because of the difficulty or dangerousness of the journey. The original manuscript pages of the 1910 Census are permanently damaged in places. Many pages of the census had torn places which had been "repaired" with cellophane tape before they were microfilmed. The tape turned the area gray upon microfilming, and there is nothing to read except some of the detailed information following the taped over name. Some areas were completely "washed out" and some so faint that recording any name was impossible. Be aware that there are names that were spelled phonetically by the Enumerator, and the Indexers, unable to figure out what he was attempting to spell, could only duplicate what was written, letter by letter. This often happened when the Enumerator was challenged by names that were unfamiliar to him. Notwithstanding handwriting that is inherently difficult to read, ink blots, faded ink, and cellophane tape, we have worked diligently to present as complete and accurate an index as possible. The publisher regrets any misspellings, omissions, or misinterpretations that may have occurred. Please report any errors to the Albuquerque Genealogical Society so they may be corrected. SPECIAL THANKS Many thanks are in order to the staff of the Special Collections library for their help, advice, and support given me in accomplishing this task, so thank you Joe Sabatini, Maxine Huang, Carolyn Reese, and Gail Rasmussen. Thanks are given to the thiity some Special Collections Library volunteers working on this total project, and special thanks are given to volunteers Charles Jensen, Ann Mossman, and Michael Van Laanen who worked at indexing this volume of Torrance County.
